bstractText>&lt;p>Policy making is about setting agendas and defining alternatives, but it is also about developing specific measures that might make policies work. Political leaders generally only have a broad grasp of the range of applied issues involved in making policy - such as how to put together legislation, organisational budgets or instructions to those charged with implementation.&amp;nbsp;They must delegate much of this policy work to bureaucrats.&amp;nbsp;This research looks at how such delegation works in six jurisdictions - the United Kingdom, France, Sweden, Germany, the United States and&amp;nbsp; the European Union.&amp;nbsp;It explores the development of a sample of administrative regulations in each jurisdiction and talks to the people who wrote them.&amp;nbsp;The patterns and norms of supervision and approval as well as the basis on which such officials exercise discretion when developing policy will be contrasted to explore cross-national variations in the conflict between hierarchy and expertise highlighted in the theoretical work of, among others, Max Weber and Alvin Gouldner.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-03-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>20358</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>0C56E205-60C8-4C73-A3B2-89EAB797986